The official unemployment rate in the 16 European Union (EU) countries that use the euro rose to 10% in December 2009 as a result of another recession.[148] Latvia had the highest unemployment rate in the EU, at 22.3% for November 2009.[149] Europe's young workers have been especially hard hit.[150] In November 2009, the unemployment rate in the EU27 for those aged 15â€“24 was 18.3%. For those under 25, the unemployment rate in Spain was 43.8%.[151] Unemployment has risen in two thirds of European countries since 2010.[152]
